/*

#see network.png

--network=host makes the Dev Container (the box on the left) share the same network 
namespace as the microVM (the outer box that contains both inner boxes).

That means the Dev Container can directly see and use all ports and services running 
inside the microVM — including the Docker MCP Services on the right (can only see 
them if those services expose ports to the host (WSL2) — as if they were on 
the same machine.

If you comment it out, the Dev Container gets its own isolated network, so it can’t 
automatically reach those services unless you explicitly connect them through a shared 
Docker network.

// PYTHON MCP SDK MODE:
// No special extensions needed beyond Python.
  No special extentions needed for Python MCP SDK Mode
  The Python MCP SDK is just a Python library installed via requirements.txt.

  PYTHON MCP SDK does not require:

        special VS Code extensions
        special system packages
        special Docker mounts
        special environment variables
        special Node tooling

  So the Dev Container already supports it by default because it includes:

        Python
        pip
        requirements.txt
        VS Code Python extensions


        Docker MCP Toolkit does need Dev Container additions
        Docker‑based MCP Toolkit requires:

            Docker socket mount
            Docker CLI
            Docker VS Code extension
            REST Client extension (optional but useful)

    So those appear in the Dev Container.

    (4) Provide both custom MCP and Docker MCP Toolkit mode
The comments and extension list support both:
Python MCP SDK mode: No special extensions, just Python and pip.
Docker MCP Toolkit mode: Docker socket (commented out for strict isolation), Docker CLI, Docker VS Code extension, REST Client.
The configuration and comments clearly distinguish between the two modes.
(5) Anything missed?
The postCreateCommand points to .devcontainer/setup.sh, but this file is not shown—ensure it installs all required dependencies (Node, Google Cloud CLI, etc.) as described in your documentation.
If you want to prevent any workspace mounting, you may need to explicitly set workspaceMount to "none" or use a Dockerfile that copies only the needed files.
If you want to allow switching between modes (strict isolation vs. Docker MCP Toolkit), consider documenting how to toggle the Docker socket mount and network settings.
The documentation and comments are clear, but make sure the actual setup.sh and requirements.txt are up to date with your intended toolchain.

  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // NETWORKING
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // The container joins the 'mcp-net' Docker network for isolation.
  // 
  // --network=mcp-net (default here):
  //   - PROS:
  //       * Isolates the Dev Container from the host network for better security.
  //       * Allows communication with other containers on 'mcp-net' (e.g., MCP microservices).
  //       * Prevents accidental exposure of services to the host.
  //   - CONS:
  //       * The Dev Container cannot directly access services running on the host unless explicitly exposed.
  //       * Requires explicit Docker network configuration for inter-container communication.
  //
  // --network=host (alternative, commented out):
  //   - PROS:
  //       * Dev Container shares the host network namespace.
  //       * Can directly access all ports/services running on the host (e.g., WSL2, host-based Docker services).
  //       * Simplifies networking for development/debugging.
  //   - CONS:
  //       * Reduces isolation—services in the container are accessible from the host.
  //       * Potential for port conflicts and security risks.
  //       * Not supported on all platforms (e.g., not on macOS).
  //
  // To allow host Docker access, uncomment the Docker socket mount below.
  
*/

{
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // MicroVM AI Agent Dev Container
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  "name": "MicroVM AI Agent Dev Container",
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // BASE IMAGE
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // We use the official Python 3.12 image directly.
  // No Dockerfile is needed because:
  //   - All required tools (Node, Google Cloud CLI, build tools, etc.)
  //     are installed via the postCreateCommand (see setup.sh).
  //   - No custom OS-level modifications or extra files are needed at build time.
  //   - This keeps the setup simple and reproducible.
  "image": "python:3.12",
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // Rootless Docker-in-Docker 
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // Instead of using the host's Docker, you run a completely independent Docker daemon 
  // inside your container that runs as a non-privileged user.
  // How it works: The container runs its own dockerd using User Namespaces. Even if a 
  // process escapes the inner Docker, it only "breaks out" into the Dev Container, not 
  // your actual laptop. Implementation: Use the docker-in-docker feature but configure it 
  // for Rootless mode.
  "features": {
    "ghcr.io/devcontainers/features/docker-in-docker:2": {
      "installDockerBuildx": true,
      "rootless": true,
      "moby": false
    }
  },
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // NETWORKING
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // The container joins the 'mcp-net' Docker network for isolation.
  // To allow host Docker access, uncomment the Docker socket mount below.
  "runArgs": [
    "--network=mcp-net",
    "--add-host=host.docker.internal:host-gateway"
    // "-v",
    // "/var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock" // Uncomment for Docker MCP Toolkit mode
  ],
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // POST-CREATE SETUP
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // All additional dependencies (Node, Google Cloud CLI, Docker network setup) are
  // installed after the container is created, using this script.
  // This approach avoids the need for a custom Dockerfile.
  // Note: The 'mcp-net' Docker network is created by setup.sh (step 9), so it will
  //       be available before services attempt to join it during later operations.
  "postCreateCommand": ".devcontainer/setup.sh",
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // VS CODE EXTENSIONS
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  "customizations": {
    "vscode": {
      "extensions": [
        // Python MCP SDK Mode (default)
        "ms-python.python",
        "ms-python.vscode-pylance",
        "ms-toolsai.jupyter",
        //"GoogleCloudTools.cloudcode", no extension needed as Google CLI not used
        // Docker MCP Toolkit Mode (optional, for microservice debugging)
        "ms-azuretools.vscode-docker",
        "humao.rest-client"
      ]
    }
  },
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // USER
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  "remoteUser": "root",
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // PORT FORWARDING
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // Applies to both MCP SDK and Docker MCP Toolkit modes.
  "forwardPorts": [
    //3000, //Node.js removed from devcontainer setup
    6333,
    5000,
    8000
    //8080 //Google CLI removed from devcontainer setup
  ]
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // WORKSPACE MOUNTING (Optional)
  // -------------------------------------------------------------------
  // By default, VS Code mounts the project root.
  // To enforce strict isolation, set workspaceMount to "none" or copy only needed files in Dockerfile.
  // "workspaceMount": "source=c:/Users/utpal/projects/code,target=/workspace/code,type=bind",
  // "workspaceFolder": "/workspace/code"
}